         <abstract>
            <p>The finance literature has produced multiple theories that are consistent with an optimal capital structure. Since no theory can definitively prescribe the optimal financial structure for an individual firm, managerial judgment may be useful in targeting the debt/equity mix. This judgment likely includes comparisons with firms in the same industry. The initial purpose of this study is to provide additional evidence on the relationship between accounting leverage measures and industrial classifications both cross-sectionally and across time. We review previous empirical work on cross-sectional differences in capital structure and examine several potential causes of the conflicting results of earlier studies. A second purpose of the study is to provide preliminary evidence on the theoretical relationship between cross-sectional differences in the use of leverage and the level of average tax shelters across industries. Thus, we attempt first to resolve some deficiencies in past empirical work on the existence of leverage differences across industries and across time and second to test a recently developed hypothesis as to why such differences might exist. Major conclusions include the following: 1) significant differences exist between mean industry financial structures; 2) these differences persist over time; 3) firms within an industry tend to converge over time to the (possibly changing) industry mean financial structure; and 4) the use of debt in industry mean financial structures tends to be inversely related to the level of tax shelters provided by depreciation, the investment tax credit, and the operating tax loss carryforward.</p>
         </abstract>
